Development of a predictive model for long-term care and support eligibility certification associated with dementia-related functional impairments: the IRIDE cohort study
Background
Predictive models have been developed to assess the future risk of dementia based on individual risk factors. Representative models include the Cardiovascular Risk Factors, Aging, and Incidence of Dementia (CAIDE) [
20
], which predicts the risk of developing dementia approximately 20 years later using midlife vascular risk factors such as age, years of education, sex, blood pressure, BMI, total cholesterol levels, physical activity, and smoking habits. Another example is the Australian National University Alzheimer's Disease Risk Index (ANU-ADRI) [
21
], which is based on self-reported data, incorporating 11 risk factors (e.g., age, sex, low educational attainment, diabetes, traumatic brain injury, depressive symptoms, smoking, and limited social networks) and four protective factors (cognitive stimulation activities, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and fish intake). Additionally, the Lifestyle for Brain Health (LIBRA) emphasizes modifiable midlife risk factors, including depression, hypertension, obesity, smoking, high cholesterol, diabetes, physical inactivity, coronary artery disease, alcohol consumption, and kidney disease [
22
]. Although slight differences are observed in the factors included in these risk assessment models, many share a common focus on vascular health indicators, such as hypertension, high cholesterol, and diabetes; physical factors such as BMI; and lifestyle-related factors including physical activity, smoking, and alcohol consumption.
Assessing future dementia risk may facilitate early preventive interventions against dementia onset. However, research on predictive models for dementia risk remains insufficient in the Asian region, and further investigation is needed to determine whether the variables used in existing models contribute similarly to prediction across different cultural backgrounds. Additionally, developing predictive models that consider not only the risk of dementia onset but also the degree of independence in daily life may contribute to more practical and early-stage dementia prevention strategies.
